      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Key Observations\n\n- **Stepwise constants (K)** dominate the database, accounting for over three-quarters of all entries. This reflects the common experimental practice of reporting equilibrium constants for successive ligand-binding steps (e.g., ML, ML₂, ML₃…).\n- **Cumulative constants (H / β)** make up about 12% of entries. These represent the overall formation constant from the free metal and free ligand directly to the MLₙ species.\n- **S-type constants** (~11%) cover solubility products and other specialized equilibrium definitions.\n\nThis distribution is typical of coordination chemistry databases, where stepwise constants are the most frequently measured and reported quantities.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (SRD-46)*",
